04310nam a22005055i 9780226389288DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20092009ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226389288  a(DE-B1597)524261  a(OCoLC)609631788  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aHQ76.3.F8bJ33 2010eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a306.76/609442221 aJackson, Julian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiving in Arcadia :bHomosexuality, Politics, and Morality in France from the Liberation to AIDS /cJulian Jackson. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b25 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE. THE BACKGROUND -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. Homosexuality in France from the Revolution to Vichy -- t2. The Shadow of the Occupation, 1942–1955 -- tPART TWO. ET IN ARCADIA EGO, 1954–1968 -- tINTRODUCTION -- t3. Beginnings, 1954–1956 -- t4. Survival, 1956–1968 -- t5. The Vision of Arcadie: Homosexuality and Ethics -- t6. Living in Arcadie -- tPART THREE. ARCADIE CONTESTED, 1968–1982 -- tINTRODUCTION -- t7. The Deluge, 1968–1972 -- t8. The Arcadie Years, 1973–1978 -- t9. The End, 1979–1982 -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Paris in 1954, a young man named André Baudry founded Arcadie, an organization for “homophiles” that would become the largest of its kind that has ever existed in France, lasting nearly thirty years. In addition to acting as the only public voice for French gays prior to the explosion of radicalism of 1968, Arcadie—with its club and review—was a social and intellectual hub, attracting support from individuals as diverse as Jean Cocteau and Michel Foucault and offering support and solidarity to thousands of isolated individuals. Yet despite its huge importance, Arcadie has largely disappeared from the historical record. The main cause of this neglect, Julian Jackson explains in Living in Arcadia, is that during the post-Stonewall era of queer activism, Baudry’s organization fell into disfavor, dismissed as conservative, conformist, and closeted. Through extensive archival research and numerous interviews with the reclusive Baudry, Jackson challenges this reductive view, uncovering Arcadie’s pioneering efforts to educate the European public about homosexuality in an era of renewed repression. In the course of relating this absorbing history, Jackson offers a startlingly original account of the history of homosexuality in modern France.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHomosexualityzFrancexHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aaids, liberation, france, morality, politics, homosexuality, sexuality, values, arcadie, subculture, homophiles, gay men, masculinity, lgbt, lgbtqia, lgbtq, queer, belonging, authenticity, radical, isolation, solidarity, michel foucault, jean cocteau, activism, repression, conformity, closet, history, nonfiction, sexual revolution, dignity, occupation, secrecy, clandestine.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022638925740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226389288423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226389288/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles